  "prompt": "[SPOILER] Why didn't Jon ask Melisandre to resurrect Rickon after he died in the war?",
  "response": "In *Game of Thrones*, Jon Snow doesn't ask Melisandre to resurrect Rickon Stark after his death during the Battle of the Bastards for several reasons:\n\n1. **Melisandre's Uncertain Power**: Melisandre's ability to resurrect someone is not something she can do on command. She had only successfully resurrected Jon Snow once, and even she seemed surprised by it. It\u2019s unclear whether she could have done it again, especially for someone else.\n\n2. **The Timing**: Rickon died during the chaos of the battle, and by the time Jon and his allies had secured Winterfell, too much time may have passed. Resurrection in the show typically requires the person to have died very recently (e.g., Jon and Beric Dondarrion). There\u2019s no indication that it could work long after death.\n\n3. **Jon's Focus**: After the battle, Jon was focused on securing Winterfell, dealing with Ramsay Bolton, and preparing for the larger threat of the White Walkers. Rickon\u2019s death, while tragic, may not have been at the forefront of his immediate concerns.\n\n4. **Melisandre's Departure**: After the battle, Melisandre was banished from the North by Jon for her role in Shireen Baratheon\u2019s burning. Even if Jon had considered asking her to resurrect Rickon, her banishment made that impossible.\n\n5. **Thematic Reasons**: From a storytelling perspective, Rickon\u2019s death served as a tragic moment to heighten the stakes of the Battle of the Bastards and to emphasize the ruthlessness of Ramsay Bolton. Bringing Rickon back would have undermined the emotional impact of his death.\n\nIn summary, a combination of practical limitations, Jon\u2019s priorities, and narrative choices prevented Jon from seeking Rickon\u2019s resurrection.",
